Let $\mathbf{v}_0 = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}.$ Then $\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} x \cos 42^\circ - y \sin 42^\circ \\ x \sin 42^\circ + y \cos 42^\circ \end{pmatrix}.$ The reflection of $\mathbf{v}_1$ over the line with direction vector $\begin{pmatrix} \cos 108^\circ \\ \sin 108^\circ \end{pmatrix}$ is given by $$\mathbf{v}_2 = 2 \begin{pmatrix} \cos 108^\circ \\ \sin 108^\circ \end{pmatrix} \left( \begin{pmatrix} \cos 108^\circ \\ \sin 108^\circ \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}_1 \right) - \mathbf{v}_1.$$ We can calculate that \begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} \cos 108^\circ \\ \sin 108^\circ \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}_1 &= \cos 108^\circ (x \cos 42^\circ - y \sin 42^\circ) + \sin 108^\circ (x \sin 42^\circ + y \cos 42^\circ) \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{3} - 1}{2 \sqrt{2}} x + \frac{\sqrt{3} + 1}{2 \sqrt{2}} y.
\end{align*} Therefore, \begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_2 &= 2 \begin{pmatrix} \cos 108^\circ \\ \sin 108^\circ \end{pmatrix} \left( \frac{\sqrt{3} - 1}{2 \sqrt{2}} x + \frac{\sqrt{3} + 1}{2 \sqrt{2}} y \right) - \mathbf{v}_1 \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{2} x + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} y \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x - \frac{1}{2} y \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*} On the other hand, the reflection of $\mathbf{v}_0$ over the line with direction vector $\begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix}$ is given by $$\mathbf{v}_2 = 2 \begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix} \left( \begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}_0 \right) - \mathbf{v}_0.$$ We can calculate that \begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}_0 &= \cos \theta x + \sin \theta y.
\end{align*} Therefore, \begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_2 &= 2 \begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix} \left( \cos \theta x + \sin \theta y \right) - \mathbf{v}_0 \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 2 \cos^2 \theta x + 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta y - x \\ 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta x + 2 \sin^2 \theta y - y \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*} Equating the two expressions for $\mathbf{v}_2$, we have \begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{2} x + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} y \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x - \frac{1}{2} y \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 2 \cos^2 \theta x + 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta y - x \\ 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta x + 2 \sin^2 \theta y - y \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*} Equating the first components, we have \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} x + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} y &= 2 \cos^2 \theta x + 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta y - x \\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{3}{2} x - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} y &= 2 \cos^2 \theta x + 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta y.
\end{align*} Equating the second components, we have \begin{align*}
\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x - \frac{1}{2} y &= 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta x + 2 \sin^2 \theta y - y \\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} x + \frac{1}{2} y &= 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta x + 2 \sin^2 \theta y.
\end{align*} We can solve this system of equations to find $\theta$.  We can multiply the first equation by $\sin \theta$ and the second equation by $\cos \theta$ and then subtract the two equations to find \begin{align*}
\frac{3}{2} \sin \theta x - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin \theta y &= 2 \cos^2 \theta \sin \theta x + 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos \theta y \\
\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cos \theta x + \frac{1}{2} \cos \theta y &= 2 \sin \theta \cos^2 \theta x + 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos \theta y \\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{3}{2} \sin \theta x - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin \theta y - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cos \theta x - \frac{1}{2} \cos \theta y &= 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta (\cos \theta - \sin \theta) x + 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta (\sin \theta - \cos \theta) y \\
\Rightarrow\qquad \left( \frac{3}{2} \sin \theta - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cos \theta \right) x - \left( \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin \theta + \frac{1}{2} \cos \theta \right) y &= 0.
\end{align*} Since this equation must hold for all $x$ and $y$, we must have \begin{align*}
\frac{3}{2} \sin \theta - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cos \theta &= 0 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad \tan \theta &= \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad \theta &= \arctan \left( \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3} \right) = \boxed{30^\circ}.
\end{align*}

