The $x$-intercepts of the graph of $y=f(x)$ are the values of $x$ such that $f(x)=0$. We can solve for these values by setting the numerator of $f(x)$ equal to zero and solving for $x$: \begin{align*}
(x-2)^2-9&=0\\
\Rightarrow\qquad (x-2)^2&=9\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x-2&=\pm3\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=2\pm3
\end{align*}Therefore, the $x$-intercepts are $x=-1$ and $x=5$. The $y$-intercept is the value of $f(0)$: \begin{align*}
